Dunno -- I've never had any problems landing "rough" on a planet, ever.

It's easy. Here's what you do:

- Get to the vicinity of the planet.
- Aim yourself at the limb of the planet and fly towards it at a reasonable
speed. You may wish to use time acceleration to various degrees.
- Eventually, the altitude indicator on the HUD comes on. Shortly thereafter,
your ship will automatically roll so that you are right side up with respect
to the ground.You've finished the hardest part already.
- Tilt the nose down a bit... fly towards the ground... reduce speed... lower
landing gear... at around 20 or 30 meters, you should have _no_ forward
velocity. Point your ship's nose straight at the horizon; let
gravity take you down the rest of the way. And _voila_ (French for "you've
landed on the planet",) you've landed on the planet. The little status
thingy should say "Landed (rough)".

Caveat: The biggest ship I've ever flown is the Constrictor I've got right
now. I've heard that larger ships, with more mass to swing around, tend to
be more difficult to land, but I have no personal experience there.

Now, here's _my_ question. How can you fuel scoop from a gas giant and then
still escape? I've fuel scooped twice -- first time, no problems, got into
the atmosphere, filled the hold, flew away. Second time, got into the
atmosphere, filled the hold, found that my forward velocity was dropping
no matter what I did with the engines. Also, in a gas giant's atmosphere
I get an Altitude: 0 meters reading on the HUD. Just another bug, I suppose?
It does make things rather confusing!

