Subject: Missiles in Frontier...
Lines: 48

...aren't quite as useless as generally believed. I've made use of them
quite well, to the extent that I generally try to keep two of them
around. Here's the tips on it:

1. Use NN500 Naval Missiles. The enemy always seems to have ECM -- but no ECM
can kill a Naval Missile. Plus, they deliver a bigger punch, if the manual
is to be believed. However, these are a Federation weapon -- they're not
available outside the Fed. So you Imperial weenies are out of luck... the
only way you're going to get a Naval Missile is up your tailpipe. >;)

2. If you want to cheat, you can fire a missile at any ship and then hit
double time acceleration. Hitting time acceleration causes all missiles
in flight to instantly reach their targets. This also counts for missiles
targeted at _you_... I don't like to take advantage of program bugs, however.

3. Playing fairly: missiles, even naval ones, are of very little use against
any ship that's small or fast-moving or both. They can and do dodge away
until the missile runs out of gas and dies. On the other hand, while running
from the missile, they will be too occupied to fire at _you_... so this may
be a handy technique to chase an enemy away to give your shields time to
recover, or you could attack them while the missile is distracting them.

4. Against Imperial Traders/Couriers or larger ships, the missile _does_
come in handy. For best results, forget everything you learned in F/A-18
Interceptor -- firing at the rear of a ship is not necessarily the best
option, as they will have more time to dodge a missile they're running from.
My favorite technique is to arm the missile then continue steering with the
mouse and engines on, while keeping a finger on the "M" key. When the other
ship approaches to make a close flyby, point the nose ahead of it, leading
the enemy, then fire. This is using the weapon as a "dumb-fire" missile, but
it tends to work. A single Naval Missile will do 50% hull damage on an
Imperial Trader, and knock down half of the shields on a heavily shielded
Panther Clipper.

Now, it may be a little cheaper to just use lasers... but honestly, I think
missiles are a lot more fun. So these tips may help you use them.

(Dream: I'd kind of like to see intership combat carried out at distances
of thousands or millions of KM and handled with launched fighter craft
and guided missiles. Lasers and focused ECM could be used against enemy
missile fire... Sigh. When is a space _battleship_ simulation gonna come
out??)

