In the message * elite/frontier/help me * Graham  wrote:

 GC> so, come on guys (and girls) - any advice (apart from buying an amiga
 GC> 1200+fast ram)? also, did the elite (i.e. version one) come out on the
 GC> amiga. if so, what was it like? if it was like the archemedes version,
 GC> i'd buy it tomorrow.

It's not very good at all. I have not seen the archie version, but I HAVE
seen the C64 version, and while the gfx is better on the Amiga port, the
enemies are dumber and features are missing. Elite on the Amiga is not a
good game, atleast not in this day and age. Elite also does not make use
of faster processors, and even break under newer operating systems, so I'd
not recommend it if it wasn't dead cheap - chances are you wont be able to
play it. It does have some of that elite feeling (you DO feel good after
wasting a Thargon!) but not like the C64 version.

It might be worth getting because it's a classic, or out of sheer nostalgia,
and it _IS_ elite so it can't be all crap, but it IS a poor port of this
great game.

Frontier, on the other hand... I don't know. I have mixed feelings. It is
a great game, it has the most impressive 3D-engine I've ever seen, and the
level of detail is incredible (from accurate celestial mechanics to working
clocks on the churches!), but it is marred by the fact that it is not a
finished game (it reminds me more of a leaked beta version!).

When the bugs are fixed and there are extra data disks available, then it
will be the best game ever (especially if they hire real artists to do the
sound and bitmapped gfx!). As it is, it is pretty and an impressive
programming feat, but it lacks the staying power of Elite. It is good for a
few weeks of playing, but I wont be playing it a year from now (as I did
with Elite... From time to time I returned to Lave to take my aggressions
out on some poor unfortunate spacepirates).
It's a great game, but it's not the earth shattering game it could have
been. 


